  "local_port": 38800,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I transfer from an international university to a US university as a US permanent resident?",
  "response": "Transferring from an international university to a US university involves several steps. As a US permanent resident, you have certain advantages, such as eligibility for in-state tuition rates at public universities and fewer visa-related complications. Here\u2019s a comprehensive guide to help you through the process:\n\n### 1. Research US Universities\n- **Identify potential universities:** Look for institutions that align with your academic goals, preferred location, and other preferences.\n- **Transfer policies:** Check each university\u2019s transfer policies, including credit transfer, GPA requirements, and application deadlines.\n\n### 2. Prepare Your Documents\n- **Transcripts:** Obtain official transcripts from your current international university. They may need to be translated and evaluated by a credential evaluation service (such as WES).\n- **Course syllabi:** Some universities may require detailed syllabi of courses you've completed to assess credit transferability.\n- **Letters of recommendation:** Secure letters from professors or academic advisors who can speak to your academic abilities and character.\n\n### 3. Standardized Tests\n- **SAT/ACT:** Some universities may require standardized test scores, even for transfer students.\n- **English proficiency:** If your previous education was not in English, you might need to take TOEFL or IELTS.\n\n### 4. Application Process\n- **Application form:** Complete the application form for each university you\u2019re applying to. This may be through the Common App, Coalition App, or the university\u2019s own application system.\n- **Personal statement/essay:** Write a compelling essay explaining your reasons for transferring and how the new university will help you achieve your academic and career goals.\n- **Application fee:** Pay the application fee for each university.\n\n### 5. Financial Planning\n- **Tuition and fees:** Research the cost of attendance and understand the financial implications.\n- **Financial aid:** As a permanent resident, you are eligible to apply for federal financial aid (FAFSA). Also, explore scholarships and grants offered by the universities.\n\n### 6. Submit Your Application\n- Ensure all required documents are submitted by the application deadlines.\n- Regularly check your application status and promptly respond to any additional information requests.\n\n### 7. Await Admission Decisions\n- Be patient and track the status of your applications.\n- Once you receive offers, compare them based on academic programs, transfer credit acceptance, financial aid packages, and other factors important to you.\n\n### 8. Transfer Credits\n- Work with the admissions and registrar\u2019s offices to determine which of your credits will transfer.\n- Discuss any discrepancies or additional requirements with the academic advisor.\n\n### 9. Visa Considerations\n- As a US permanent resident, you don\u2019t need a student visa, but you should inform the university of your status.\n- Ensure your permanent residency documents are in order.\n\n### 10. Transition to the US University\n- **Orientation:** Attend orientation programs designed for transfer students.\n- **Housing:** Arrange for on-campus or off-campus housing.\n- **Academic advising:** Meet with academic advisors to plan your course schedule and understand the university\u2019s academic policies.\n\n### 11. Additional Tips\n- **Networking:** Connect with current students and faculty to get insights into the university culture and academic environment.\n- **Support services:** Utilize support services such as tutoring, counseling, and career services offered by the university.\n\nBy following these steps, you can navigate the transfer process smoothly and integrate into your new academic environment successfully. Good luck!",
